 within one of the largest unfragmented landscapes in North America. Arguably the world's largest boreal inland delta, it is renowned for its biological productivity and is a central feature of a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Yet the delta and its indigenous cultures lie downstream of Alberta's bitumen sands, whose exploitation comprises one of the largest industrial projects in the world. Kevin Timoney provides an authoritative synthesis of the science and history of the delta, describing its ecology, unraveling its millennia-long history, and addressing its uncertain future. Scientists, students, leaders in the energy sector, government officials and policy makers, and conscientious citizens everywhere should read this lively work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiotic communitiesxAlbertaxPeace-Athabasca Delta. 0aBiotic communitieszAlbertazPeace-Athabasca Delta. 0aNatural historyxAlbertaxPeace-Athabasca Delta. 0aNatural historyzAlbertazPeace-Athabasca Delta. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexAlberta. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezAlberta. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  aEcology.  aNature.  aPetroleum Industry.  aRivers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088864802040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780888648020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780888648020/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles